'''Vidya Balan''' (pronounced {{IPA-hns|<U+028B><U+026A>d<U+032A>ja<U+02D0> ba<U+02D0>l<U+0259>n|}}; born 1 January 1978)<ref>{{cite news|title=Vidya Balan celebrates her 31st birthday|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Vidya-Balan-celebrates-her-31st-birthday/Article1-492473.aspx|date=31 December 2009|work=Hindustan Times|accessdate=25 August 2010}}</ref> is an Indian film actress, who appears in [[Bollywood|Hindi]], [[Bengali cinema|Bengali]] and [[Malayalam cinema|Malayalam]] language films. At age sixteen, Balan landed her first acting role in the [[sitcom]] ''[[Hum Paanch (TV series)|Hum Paanch]]'' (1995). After making several unsuccessful attempts to start a career in film, she acted in television commercials and music videos. In 2003, she made her feature film debut with the independent Bengali drama ''[[Bhalo Theko]]''.

In 2005, Balan garnered praise for her first Hindi film, ''[[Parineeta (2005 film)|Parineeta]]'', and followed it with a leading role in the [[blockbuster (entertainment)|blockbuster]] ''[[Lage Raho Munna Bhai]]'' (2006). Her subsequent portrayal of glamorous characters in the films ''[[Heyy Babyy]]'' (2007) and ''[[Kismat Konnection]]'' (2008) met with negative comments from film critics. 2009, however, marked the beginning of the most successful period in Balan's career as she portrayed five consecutive roles to wide critical acclaim in ''[[Paa (film)|Paa]]'' (2009), ''[[Ishqiya]]'' (2010), ''[[No One Killed Jessica]]'' (2011), ''[[The Dirty Picture]]'' (2011), and ''[[Kahaani]]'' (2012). These roles have fetched her the tag of a "female hero" and established her as a leading contemporary actress of Hindi cinema.<ref>{{cite news|work=Deccan Chronicle|last=Kapoor|first=Reena|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/bollywood/vidya-snubs-%E2%80%98heroes%E2%80%99-242|date=4 June 2012|accessdate=7 October 2012|title=Vidya snubs the 'heroes'}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=The Times of India|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-01-03/news-interviews/30581535_1_vidya-balan-silk-smitha-sabrina-lal|date=5 January 2012|accessdate=7 January 2012|author=Iyer, Meena|title=`What's left for Vidya Balan to do in 2012'}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Bhattacharya|first=Roshmila|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/Vidya-Balan-rules-BO-with-biggest-grossing-woman-centric-films/Article1-839343.aspx|title=Vidya Balan rules BO with biggest grossing woman-centric films|work=Hindustan Times|accessdate=23 September 2012|date=12 April 2012}}</ref>

Balan has received one [[National Film Award]], four [[Filmfare Awards]] and four [[Screen Awards]]. She initially drew criticism for her weight and dress sense, but was later credited in the media for retaining her individuality and breaking stereotypes of a Hindi film heroine. Balan is a social activist and supports the cause of women empowerment. She is in a relationship with film producer [[Siddharth Roy Kapur]].

==Early life and background==
Vidya Balan was born on 1 January 1978 in [[Ottapalam]], a town in the [[Palakkad District]] of [[Kerala]], to P. R. Balan, currently the Vice President of [[ETC Bollywood Business|ETC India]], and Saraswathy Balan, a homemaker.<ref name="something"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/OVER-THE-YEARS-Vidya-Balan-goes-from-geek-to-haute/Article1-934078.aspx |title=Over the years: Vidya Balan from geek to haute!|author=Bansal, Robin|date=22 September 2012|work=Hindustan Times|accessdate=24 September 2012}}</ref> According to Balan, they speak both [[Tamil language|Tamil]] and [[Malayalam]] at home; she is also well versed in Hindi, [[Marathi language|Marathi]], English and [[Bengali language|Bengali]].<ref>{{cite news|work=The Hindu|url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2007/02/16/stories/2007021600410100.htm|date=16 February 2007|accessdate=9 August 2011|author=Siddiqui, Rana|title=`It's a dream come true'}}</ref> Her elder sister, Priya Balan, works in the field of advertising.<ref name="something">{{cite news|title=There's something about Vidya|url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1168964461.html |work=Hindustan Times {{Subscription required|via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}|accessdate=23 September 2012|date=25 November 2006}}</ref>

Balan grew up in the suburban neighbourhood of [[Chembur|Chembur, Mumbai]] and was schooled at St. Anthony Girls' High School.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celeb diary: Vidya Balan|url=http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2010/feb/040210-Celeb-Dairy-Vidya-Balan.htm|accessdate=24 May 2012|work=Mid Day|date=4 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Davane|first=Mrugaya|title=Chembur will always be our home|url=http://www.mid-day.com/metro/2006/jun/139591.htm|accessdate=24 May 2012|work=Mid Day|date=16 June 2006}}</ref> Balan aspired to make a career in film from a young age and was inspired by the work of actors [[Shabana Azmi]] and [[Madhuri Dixit]].<ref name="rules"/><ref>{{cite web|publisher=IBNLive|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/madhuri-was-my-inspiration-in-life-vidya-balan/218414-8-66.html|date=6 January 2012|accessdate=13 October 2012|title=Madhuri is my inspiration in life: Vidya Balan}}</ref> At the age of sixteen, Balan starred in the first season of [[Ekta Kapoor]]'s sitcom ''[[Hum Paanch (TV series)|Hum Paanch]]'', as Radhika, a bespectacled teenager.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ganguly|first=Pritwish|title=I said no to Ekta: Vidya Balan|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-10-22/news-interviews/28271540_1_tv-debut-vidya-balan-s-homepage-audition |accessdate=23 September 2012|work=The Times of India|date=22 October 2010}}</ref><ref name="tree">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1100725/jsp/7days/story_12723277.jsp|title=<U+2018>It could have been George Clooney or a tree. I would have made love to the tree if I had to<U+2019>|first=Draupadi|last=Rohera|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=19 November 2012|date=25 June 2010}}</ref> Following the success of the show, Balan refused [[Anurag Basu]]'s offer to star as the lead of a television soap opera, as she wanted to concentrate on making a film career.<ref name="native">{{cite news|last=Bamzai|first=Kaveree|title=Return of the native|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/Return+of+the+native/1/82489.html|accessdate=23 September 2012|work=India Today|date=4 February 2010|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6CJF2Gxwb|archivedate=20 November 2012}}</ref> Her parents were supportive of her decision to become an actress, but encouraged her to complete her education first.<ref name="rules">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/Why-Vidya-Balan-rules/Article1-783531.aspx |title=Why Vidya Balan rules|author=Sanghvi, Vir|date=17 December 2011|work=Hindustan Times|accessdate=11 January 2012}}</ref> She thus attended [[St. Xavier's College, Mumbai|St. Xavier's College]] to pursue a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[sociology]] and later earned a [[master's degree]] from the [[University of Mumbai]].<ref>{{cite news|work=The Times of India|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-01-09/news-interviews/28367559_1_sociology-films-khar|date=9 January 2011|accessdate=23 August 2012|title=Sociology was my major subject: Vidya}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Just how educated are our Bollywood heroines?|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-just-how-educated-are-bollywood-heroines/20120118.htm|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=20 November 2012|date=18 January 2012}}</ref>

==Career==
===Struggle and debut (2000<U+2013>03)===
While pursuing her master's degree, Balan was cast as the female lead in the [[Malayalam cinema|Malayalam film]] ''Chakram'', opposite [[Mohanlal]], and was subsequently signed on for twelve other Malayalam language films.<ref name="rules"/> However, due to production difficulties, ''Chakram'' was shelved.<ref name="beginning"/> The postponement of a film starring Mohanlal was an unheard of occurrence in Malayalam cinema and film producers blamed her for bringing "bad luck" to the project; labelled her as a "jinx" and replaced her in all the films that she had been contracted for.<ref name="rules"/> She then shifted focus to [[Tamil cinema]]. In 2001, she was cast as the female lead in [[N. Linguswamy]]'s ''[[Run (2002 film)|Run]]'' (2002). However, after completing the first [[shooting schedule]] of the film, she was unceremoniously dropped and replaced by [[Meera Jasmine]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Vidya magic!|publisher=Sify.com|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/the-vidya-magic-news-tamil-kkfv22bcabh.html|accessdate=23 November 2006|date=7 July 2005}}</ref> She was signed up under false pretences for a [[sex comedy]], a genre she was then uncomfortable with, and thus decided to leave the project.<ref name="rules"/> Thereafter, she signed on for a third Tamil film, ''[[Manasellam]]'' (2003), but was replaced by [[Trisha Krishnan]] as the director was dissatisfied with her work.<ref>{{cite news|title=When Vidya Balan was kicked out|work=The Times of India|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-13/did-you-know-/31160200_1_vidya-balan-hindi-films-south-filmmakers|accessdate=23 March 2012|date=7 July 2005}}</ref> 

After failing to start a film career, Balan appeared in approximately sixty television commercials and in music videos for [[Euphoria (Indian band)|Euphoria]] and [[Shubha Mudgal]]; a majority of these were directed by [[Pradeep Sarkar]].<ref name="native"/><ref>{{cite news|title= Stand-out act four not-so-new newcomers have found critical acclaim in breakthrough roles this year. Now all they need is stardom |url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-10956992.html |work=India Today {{Subscription required|via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}|accessdate= 23 September 2012|date=18 July 2005}}</ref> In 2003, she was signed on by [[Goutam Halder]] for his independent [[Bengali cinema|Bengali]] drama ''[[Bhalo Theko]]''; her first film release.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bhalo Theko|url=http://www.screenindia.com/news/Bhalo-Theko/5500/ |work=Screen|accessdate=1 April 2012|date=15 August 2003}}</ref> Her portrayal of Anandi, a young woman reminiscing about her past, won her an [[Anandalok Awards|Anandalok Purashkar]] for Best Actress.<ref>{{cite news|title=I feel I was Bengali in my last life: Vidya Balan|url= http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/Entertainment/I-feel-I-was-Bengali-in-my-last-life-Vidya-Balan/Article1-273183.aspx|work=Hindustan Times|accessdate=23 March 2012|date=1 February 2008}}</ref>

===Breakthrough (2005<U+2013>08)===
In 2005, Balan made her Hindi film debut with Pradeep Sarkar's musical drama ''[[Parineeta (2005 film)|Parineeta]]''. Before being cast for the film, Balan had to undergo extensive auditions for a period of 6 months.<ref name="beginning">{{cite web|accessdate=23 October 2007 |first=Ronjita |last=Kulkarni|url=http://specials.rediff.com/movies/2005/jun/08vidya2.htm |title=Meet the new girl in Saif's life|publisher=Rediff.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=20 November 2012|date=1 January 2009|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/1158478/Small-people-with-big-egosnot-for-me-Vidhu-Vinod-Chopra|title=Small people with big egos, not for me!|publisher=Bollywood Hungama}}</ref> The film, an adaptation of [[Sarat Chandra Chattopadhyay]]'s [[Parineeta|novel of the same name]], narrated the love story of an idealist Lalita (Balan) and an egoist Shekhar ([[Saif Ali Khan]]), the son of a capitalist businessman.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1050611/asp/nation/story_4854277.asp|title=Parineeta breathes Bengal among the tulips |first=Pratim D. |last=Gupta |date=10 June 2005|accessdate=9 August 2011|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> Her performance in the film was praised by critics;<ref name="tree"/> Derek Elley from ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote, " An acting revelation is Tamil newcomer Balan, whose devoted but dignified Lalita is the picture's heart and soul."<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=27 October 2007|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117929519.html?categoryId=31&cs=1 |title=Parineeta: Film review |first=Derek |last=Elley |work=Variety |date=7 February 2006}}</ref> ''Parineeta'' fetched her a [[Filmfare Best Female Debut Award|Best Debut (Female)]] award and a nomination for [[Filmfare Best Actress Award|Best Actress]] at the annual [[Filmfare Awards]] ceremony.<ref name="oldawards">{{cite web|url=http://oldbh.bollywoodhungama.com/celebrities/awards/13469/index.html|title=Vidya Balan: Awards & nominations|accessdate=23 July 2010|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20100409130237/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/celebrities/awards/13469/index.html|archivedate=6 August 2010}}</ref>

The following year, Balan appeared opposite [[Sanjay Dutt]] in [[Rajkumar Hirani]]'s comedy film ''[[Lage Raho Munna Bhai]]''. She portrayed the role of Jhanvi, a [[Radio jockey|radio jockey]] and the love interest of the protagonist [[Munna Bhai]]. To prepare for her role, she met with a couple of radio jockeys and watched them at work.<ref name=hindusiddiqui>{{Cite news | first = Rana | last = Siddiqui | title = The grace of Munnabhai | url =http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/fr/2006/09/01/stories/2006090102090100.htm |work=The Hindu| date = 1 September 2006 | accessdate =20 April 2007}}</ref> Her performance was critically well received,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/masands-verdict-lage-raho-munnabhai/20366-8.html|title=Masand's verdict: Lage Raho Munnabhai |publisher=IBNLive|accessdate=7 July 2011}}</ref> and the film emerged as a [[blockbuster (entertainment)|blockbuster]] with gross earnings of {{INRConvert|118.57|c}}.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=BoxOfficeIndia|title=Box office 2006|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=212&catName=MjAwNg==|accessdate=9 January 2008}}</ref>

In 2007, Balan featured in a supporting role in [[Mani Ratnam]]'s semi-biographical drama ''[[Guru (2007 film)|Guru]]'' as a woman suffering from [[Multiple Sclerosis|multiple sclerosis]]. The film, which starred [[Mithun Chakraborty]], [[Abhishek Bachchan]], [[Aishwarya Rai Bachchan]], and [[R. Madhavan]] in leading roles, performed well at the box office.<ref name="Box Office 2007">{{cite web|title=Box office 2007|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=214&catName=MjAwNw==|publisher=BoxOfficeIndia|accessdate=9 January 2008}}</ref> However, film critics [[Khalid Mohamed]] and [[Raja Sen]] noted that her "talent was wasted" in a "minuscule role".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/REVIEW-Guru-Good-value-for-Mani/Article1-199345.aspx|title=Guru: Good value for Mani |work=Hindustan Times |accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2007/jan/12guru.htm |title=Watch Guru for the actors|publisher=Rediff.com |accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref>
Her next release was [[Nikhil Advani]]'s ''[[Salaam-e-Ishq: A Tribute To Love]]'', a romantic comedy featuring an [[ensemble cast]], in which she was paired opposite [[John Abraham (actor)|John Abraham]]. The film, which narrated six individual love stories, saw Balan play the role of a television reporter, Tehzeeb Hussain, suffering from a [[Memory loss|memory loss condition]]. The film, which was a critical and commercial failure,<ref name="Box Office 2007"/> generated positive reviews for Balan. Sukanya Verma of [[Rediff.com]] wrote,  "Vidya's transformation from a self-assured working woman to a helpless, vulnerable person is superb."<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Rediff.com| title=Salaam-e-Ishq: Stars shine in mediocre film |url=http://in.rediff.com/movies/2007/jan/26salaam.htm | accessdate=2 May 2007}}</ref>

Balan then took a supporting role in [[Vidhu Vinod Chopra]]'s suspense thriller ''[[Eklavya: The Royal Guard]]'', alongside [[Amitabh Bachchan]], [[Boman Irani]], [[Sharmila Tagore]], Saif Ali Khan, and Sanjay Dutt. The film, which flopped commercially, met with positive critical reviews and was selected as [[List of India's official entries to the Oscars|India's official entry to the Oscars]] for the [[80th Academy Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Eklavya sent to Oscars|last=Dasgupta|first=Priyanka|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2007-09-26/news-interviews/27996379_1_eklavya-official-entry-oscar-entry|accessdate=13 October 2012|date=26 September 2007|work=The Times of India}}</ref> She was later cast as Isha Sahni, a single mother, in [[Sajid Khan (director)|Sajid Khan]]'s ''[[Heyy Babyy]]'', alongside co-stars [[Akshay Kumar]], [[Ritesh Deshmukh]], and [[Fardeen Khan]]. The comedy film was a box-office success,<ref name="Box Office 2007"/> but garnered negative reviews from critics, as did Balan's performance; [[CNN-IBN]]'s [[Rajeev Masand]] criticised her wardrobe and make-up, and considered her the "sore thumb" of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://ibnlive.in.com/news/review-heyy-babyy--is-gross-comedy-overthetop-drama/47410-8.html |title=Masand's verdict: Heyy Babyy|publisher=IBNLive|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref><ref name="Publishing2008">{{cite book|author=Outlook Publishing|title=Outlook|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=PjEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA69|accessdate=10 June 2012|date=3 March 2008|publisher=Outlook Publishing|page=68}}</ref>

Balan's final film in 2007 was [[Priyadarshan]]'s [[psychological thriller]] ''[[Bhool Bhulaiyaa]]'', a remake of the Malayalam film ''[[Manichitrathazhu]]'' (1993). Balan featured as Avani Chaturvedi (a character played by [[Shobana]] in the Malayalam original), a woman suffering from [[Dissociative Identity Disorder|dissociative identity disorder]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=15 October 2012|date=11 October 2007|url=http://specials.rediff.com/movies/2007/oct/11sl3.htm|title=Who's who in Bhool Bhulaiyaa|publisher=Rediff.com}}</ref> Co-starring [[Shiney Ahuja]], Akshay Kumar, and [[Ameesha Patel]], ''Bhool Bhulaiyaa'' was a commercial success with a worldwide revenue of over {{INRConvert|83|c}}.<ref name="Box Office 2007"/> Reviewers, while being generally negative of the film, were appreciative of Balan's performance. Writing for ''[[Hindustan Times]]'', Khalid Mohamed described her as "bankably likeable" and  [[Bollywood Hungama]]'s [[Taran Adarsh]] labelled her as "splendid".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Reviews/Review-Bhool-Bhulaiya/Article1-252219.aspx|title=Review: Bhool Bhulaiya|first=Khalid |last=Mohamed|date=12 October 2007|accessdate=15 October 2012|work=Hindustan Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/criticreview/id/54360|title=Bhool Bhulaiyaa review|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|author= Adarsh, Taran|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref> The role earned Balan a second Filmfare nomination in the Best Actress category.<ref name="oldawards"/>

In 2008's [[social film]] ''[[Halla Bol]]'', Balan played a supporting role alongside [[Ajay Devgn]] and [[Pankaj Kapur]]. The film was based on the life of activist [[Safdar Hashmi]], who was killed by political rivals while performing on a street play (by the name of ''Halla Bol'') in 1989.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/Entertainment/Halla-Bol-based-on-Safdar-Hashmi-Rajkumar-Santoshi/Article1-236270.aspx|title=Halla Bol based on Safdar Hashmi: Rajkumar Santoshi|work=Hindustan Times|date=12 July 2007|accessdate=20 November 2012}}</ref> The film was a critical failure.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Reviews/Review-Halla-Bol/Article1-268739.aspx |title=Review: Halla Bol|work=Hindustan Times|author=Mohamed, Khalid|date=11 January 2008|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref> Later that year, she co-starred with [[Shahid Kapoor]] in [[Aziz Mirza]]'s romantic comedy ''[[Kismat Konnection]]''. A commercial failure,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=215&catName=MjAwOA== |title=Box office 2008|publisher=BoxOfficeIndia|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref> the film and her performance generated a negative response; critic Sonia Chopra commented, "[Balan] is made to look downright drab. The haircut is unflattering, the make-up too plain, the clothes usually in off-white or brown. Plus the character is repetitive and reminds us of the one she played in ''Lage Raho Munnabhai''."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/bollywood/review.php?id=14719095&ctid=5&cid=2425|title=Review 2: Kismat Konnection|last=Chopra|first=Sonia|publisher=Sify.com|accessdate=9 January 2012|date=18 July 2008}}</ref>

===Success and critical acclaim (2009 onwards)===
In 2009, Balan played the role of Vidya, an unwed [[gynaecologist]] struggling with her 12-year-old son's [[progeria syndrome]], in the [[R. Balki]]-directed [[dramedy]] ''[[Paa (film)|Paa]]''. Amitabh Bachchan played the role of Balan's son and Abhishek Bachchan played the titular character. Well received by critics, the film has been described as a major turning point in her career.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vidya Balan: Raring to go!|work=The Times of India|author=Kazmi, Nikhat|date=3 December 2009|accessdate=25 August 2010|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-01-01/news-interviews/28146207_1_vidya-balan-paa-happy-new-year}}</ref> Sukanya Verma compared her acting style to that of [[Dimple Kapadia]] and noted, "Balan is poignant yet restrained and projects an impressive figure of grace and integrity";<ref>{{cite web|title=Watch Paa for Auro|publisher=Rediff.com|author=Verma, Sukanya|date=4 December 2009|accessdate=25 August 2010|url=http://movies.rediff.com/report/2009/dec/04/review-watch-paa-for-auro.htm}}</ref> [[Nikhat Kazmi]] from ''[[The Times of India]]'' further argued that Balan was successful in lending a "rare dignity to the image of the Bollywood mom."<ref>{{cite news|title=Review: Paa|author=Kazmi, Nikhat|date=3 December 2009|accessdate=25 August 2010|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/hindi/Paa/moviereview/5297226.cms|work=The Times Of India}}</ref> Her portrayal ultimately fetched her a Filmfare Award for Best Actress and a [[Screen Award for Best Actress]], among other wins.<ref name="oldawards"/>

Balan followed the success of ''Paa'' with [[Vishal Bhardwaj]]'s ''[[Ishqiya]]'' (2010), a [[black comedy]] directed by debutant [[Abhishek Chaubey]]; co-starring [[Naseeruddin Shah]], [[Arshad Warsi]], and [[Salman Shahid]]. Balan's role was that of Krishna Verma, a sexually manipulative woman. Balan described her character as "an epitome of grey" and a departure from the conventional portrayal of women in cinema.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vidya Balan in never seen before role in 'Ishqiya'|date=26 January 2010|accessdate=16 October 2012|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/movies/article94956.ece|work=The Hindu}}</ref> In preparation for her part, she undertook professional training to speak in the local [[Uttar Pradesh]]-dialect.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vidya Balan takes acting lessons from Naseer|date=29 September 2008|accessdate=16 October 2012|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report_vidya-balan-takes-acting-lessons-from-naseer_1194161|work=Daily News and Analysis}}</ref> The feature as well as her performance received critical acclaim;  [[Anupama Chopra]] of [[NDTV]] stated, "Balan<U+2019>s smoldering looks scorch the screen even as her eyes hint at tragedy. She proves that she is miles ahead of the cookie cutter Barbie dolls that clutter Bollywood and that sensuality has very little to do with showing skin."<ref>{{cite web |title=Review : Ishqiya |url= http://movies.ndtv.com/movie_Review.aspx?id=473&ShowID=503|author=Chopra, Anupama|date=29 January 2010 |publisher=NDTV|accessdate=9 January 2011}}</ref> Her work in the film earned Balan a [[Filmfare Critics Award for Best Actress]], a second consecutive Best Actress award at Screen and a nomination for Best Actress at Filmfare.<ref name="awards"/>

[[File:Tusshar Kapoor, Vidya Balan, Emraan Hashmi at The Dirty Picture audio release (10).jpg|thumb|left|alt=A woman poses in between two men. She is wearing a red sari with white polka dots. The man to her left is wearing a white suit with a shiny, black shirt. The man to her right is wearing a black shirt with black trousers and black-rimmed spectacles.|Balan with co-stars [[Tusshar Kapoor]] (left) and Emraan Hashmi at the audio release of ''The Dirty Picture''. Her performance in the film met with unanimous acclaim and among other wins, fetched her a National Award and a Filmfare Award for Best Actress]]
Balan's first release of 2011 was [[Raj Kumar Gupta]]'s semi-biographical thriller ''[[No One Killed Jessica]]'', alongside [[Rani Mukerji]]. The film, based on the [[Jessica Lal]] murder case, saw Balan portray the real-life character of Sabrina Lal, Jessica's reticent sister. While preparing for her role, Balan did not meet Lal on the insistence of Gupta as "the Sabrina [...] today is different from the Sabrina a decade ago, [when] the story begins".<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article960860.ece |title=Take Two|last=Devi Dundoo|first=Sangeetha |date=25 December 2010|accessdate=11 January 2012|work=The Hindu}}</ref> ''No One Killed Jessica'' met with contrasting reviews from critics, but Balan's performance was particularly praised. ''[[The Hindu]]'' remarked on Balan's ability to be "in sublime control over her emotions"<ref>{{cite news|title=The sledgehammer wants to be subtle|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article1073041.ece|last=Kamath|first= Sudhish|date=29 January 2012|work=The Hindu|accessdate=8 January 2011}}</ref> and Savera Someshwar of Rediff.com added that "her hesitant body language, her faith, her helplessness, her rage, her sorrow and her gratitude all come across beautifully".<ref>{{cite web|title=Review: No One Killed Jessica could have been better|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/no-one-killed-jessica-review/20110106.htm|last=Someshwar|first= Savera|date=6 January 2012|publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=8 October 2012}}</ref> The film had net earnings of {{INRConvert|49|c}} and was noted for being a commercial success despite the absence of a male lead.<ref name="boxoffice2011">{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/bollywood-rediscovered-mega-hits-in-2011/212464-8-66.html|title=Bollywood rediscovered mega hits in 2011|publisher=IBNLive|accessdate=17 December 2011|date=16 December 2011}}</ref> Balan earned another Filmfare nomination in the Best Actress category for the film.<ref>{{cite web|title= Nominations for 57th Idea Filmfare Awards 2011|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/celebrities/features/type/view/id/2974/2974|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=11 January 2011|date=11 January 2011}}</ref> In March 2011, a retrospective of Balan's films was held in Australia, as part of the film festival [[Bollywood and Beyond|Bollywood & Beyond]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|title=Indian film festival in Australia to screen retrospective of Vidya Balan's films|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/1295329/Indian-Film-Festival-in-Australia-to-screen-retrospective-of-Vidya-Balans-films|date=15 March 2011|accessdate=13 March 2011}}</ref> That same year, Balan featured in a [[guest appearance]] in [[Santosh Sivan]]'s Malayalam language [[fantasy film]] ''[[Urumi (film)|Urumi]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vidya to dub in Malayalam for Urumi|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-02-27/news-interviews/28637924_1_malayalam-film-vidya-balan-urumi|date=27 February 2012|work=The Times of India|accessdate=20 November 2012}}</ref> 

Balan's next appearance was in Ekta Kapoor's ''[[The Dirty Picture (2011 film)|The Dirty Picture]]'', a biopic based on the life and death of the controversial Indian actress [[Silk Smitha]].<ref>{{cite news|work=The Hindu|author=Kumar, Anuj|title=What an odd one!|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article1075100.ece|date=9 January 2011|accessdate=9 January 2011}}</ref> Balan was cast as Silk, who was<U+2014>in Balan's words<U+2014>"known for her brazenness and in-your-face sexuality."<ref>{{cite web|publisher=IBNLive|title=Silk is sexy, desirable, but not sleazy: Vidya|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/silk-is-sexy-desirable-but-not-sleazy-vidya/206962-8-66.html|date=29 November 2011|accessdate=3 December 2011}}</ref> She described the role as the "boldest" she had ever played, one that "required a lot of mental preparation," and to look the part, she gained {{convert|12|kg|lb|0}}.<ref>{{cite news|work=Hindustan Times|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/I-gained-12-kilograms-for-The-Dirty-Picture-Vidya-Balan/Article1-776180.aspx|agency=ANI|date=30 November 2011|accessdate=2 December 2011|title=I gained 12 kilograms for The Dirty Picture: Vidya Balan}}</ref> The film opened to major critical acclaim,<ref>{{cite news|work=Hindustan Times|title=Critics go gaga over The Dirty Picture|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/Critics-go-gaga-over-The-Dirty-Picture/Article1-776922.aspx |date=2 December 2011|accessdate=2 December 2011}}</ref> and Balan received unanimous praise for her portrayal which several reviewers regarded as her best performance to date. Khalid Mohamed observed, "She<U+2019>s extraordinary: gutsy, consistently in character and unafraid of exposing her darker side. Here<U+2019>s the kind of complex performance which you haven<U+2019>t evidenced in years and years."<ref>{{cite news|work=Deccan Chronicle|author=Mohamed, Khalid|date=2 December 2011|accessdate=2 December 2011|title=The Dirty Picture review: A touch of raw Silk|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/bollywood/dirty-picture-review-touch-raw-silk-688}}</ref> Her director [[Milan Luthria]] described her as the contemporary claimant of the "sex-symbol" title, and compared her "voluptuousness" to the likes of yesteryear actresses [[Sridevi]] and [[Vyjayanthimala]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-12-01/news-interviews/30459254_1_vidya-balan-naseeruddin-shah-milan-luthria|title=Vidya Balan has a unique sex-appeal: Milan Luthria|work=The Times of India|date=1 December 2011|accessdate=1 December 2011}}</ref> The film was eventually declared a blockbuster,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3802&nCat=|title=Dirty Picture touches 100 crore|publisher=BoxOfficeIndia|accessdate=14 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Dirty Picture first week business|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3794&nCat= |date=12 December 2011|publisher=BoxOfficeIndia|accessdate=12 December 2011}}</ref> earning {{INRConvert|117|c}} worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=3944&nCat=|title=2011 worldwide figures|publisher=BoxOfficeIndia|accessdate=20 January 2011}}</ref> Balan won a second Filmfare Award, a third consecutive Screen Award, and a [[National Film Award for Best Actress]].<ref>{{cite web|title=National Awards: Vidya Balan gets best actress for 'The Dirty Picture' |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/national-awards-vidya-balan-gets-best-actress/236998-8-66.html|publisher=IBNLive|accessdate=30 September 2012}}</ref><ref name="awards">{{cite web|url= http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/celebritymicro/awards/id/8098|title=Vidya Balan&nbsp;<U+2014> Awards|accessdate=25 August 2010|publisher=Bollywood Hungama}}</ref>

For her next feature film, Balan starred as Vidya Bagchi, a pregnant woman in search of her missing husband in [[Sujoy Ghosh]]'s ''[[Kahaani]]'' (2012). The thriller, set in the city of [[Kolkata]] during the [[Durga Puja]] festivities, met with wide critical acclaim. To lend authenticity to her part, Balan met several pregnant women and learnt about their lifestyle.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/vidya-balan-gets-into-character-of-pregnant-woman-for--kahaani-/905582|title=Vidya Balan gets into character of pregnant woman for 'Kahaani'|work=The Indian Express|accessdate=15 October 2012|date=30 January 2012}}</ref> She generated public and media attention by wearing a fake baby bump during the film's promotional activities.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kelkar Dabholkar|first=Reshma|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-02-21/news-interviews/31078998_1_kahaani-vidya-balan-sujoy-ghosh|title=Vidya Balan's baby bump?|work=The Times of India|accessdate=21 February 2012|date=18 October 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Vidya Balan rides BEST bus to promote her Kahaani|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/vidya-balan-rides-best-bus-to-promote-her-kahaani/1/175688.html|date=28 February 2012 |work=India Today|accessdate=18 October 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6CJF5HHUL|archivedate=20 November 2012}}</ref> Balan received further appreciation for her performance in ''Kahaani''. Subhash K. Jha praised Balan's portrayal of "grace under pressure" as "measured and skilled"; Pratim D. Gupta of ''[[The Telegraph (Kolkata)|The Telegraph]]'' added that she "gets into the physicality of a pregnant woman with unfailing mastery".<ref>{{cite web |title=Review: Kahaani |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/movie_review.aspx?id=689|author=Jha, Subhash K.|date=9 March 2012|publisher=NDTV|accessdate=15 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120310/jsp/entertainment/story_15231247.jsp#.T3F0dEoQgrU|title=What a ''Kahaani''|first=Pratim D.|last=Gupta|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=27 March 2012|date=10 March 2012}}</ref> ''Kahaani'' emerged as a major commercial success both at the domestic and international box office, with revenues of over {{INRConvert|104|c}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Bollywood/Vidya-Balan-s-Kahaani-completes-50-days-grosses-104-cr-worldwide/Article1-847121.aspx|title=Vidya Balan's Kahaani completes 50 days, grosses Rs. 104 cr worldwide|work=Hindustan Times|accessdate=27 April 2012|date=27 April 2012 }}</ref> 

As of August 2012, Balan has been signed on for Raj Kumar Gupta's black comedy ''[[Ghanchakkar (film)|Ghanchakkar]]'', alongside [[Emraan Hashmi]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/vidya-to-show-her-comic-side-in-ghanchakkar/91616|title=Vidya to show her comic side in 'Ghanchakkar'|date=24 February 2012|work=The Indian Express|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref> and [[Saket Chaudhary]]'s romance ''[[Shaadi Ke Side Effects]]'', opposite [[Farhan Akhtar]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-06-04/news-interviews/32007467_1_skse-farhan-akhtar-sequel | title=Vidya, Farhan to team up for a sequel |work=The Times of India | date=4 June 2012 | accessdate=7 August 2012 | author=KBR, Upala}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Balan lives with her parents in [[Khar, Mumbai|Khar]], a suburban neighbourhood in Mumbai.<ref>{{cite news|work=The Times of India|last=Lalwani|first=Vickey|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-02-18/news-interviews/28120417_1_vidya-balan-chembur-new-house|date=18 February 2010|accessdate=7 January 2012|title=Vidya Balan buys a new house}}</ref> She is trained in [[carnatic music]] and has briefly studied the dance forms of ''[[Bharatnatyam]]'' and ''[[Kathak]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report_the-right-man-hasn-t-come-along-yet-vidya-balan_1089724 |title=The right man hasn't come along yet: Vidya Balan|work=Daily News and Analysis|accessdate=24 September 2012|date=9 April 2007}}</ref> Regarding her religious affiliations, Balan said, "I am a person with a lot of faith and I have conversations [with God] all the time but I am not so religious in the conventional, organised sense".<ref name="rules"/> She practices vegetarianism and was listed as "India's hottest vegetarian" in a poll conducted by [[PETA]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vyavahare|first=Renuka|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-01-18/news-interviews/28366462_1_vegetarian-diet-vidya-balan-top-contender|title=Vidya's India's hottest vegetarian|work=The Times of India|accessdate=24 September 2012|date=18 January 2011}}</ref> Her weight fluctuations over the years have been the subject of substantial media coverage in India.<ref>{{cite news|last=Baliga|first=Shashi|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/magazine/article3006462.ece|title='It was liberating to be Silk'|work=The Hindu|accessdate=17 October 2012|date=17 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Vyavahare|first=Renuka|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-05-31/news-interviews/31920503_1_vidya-balan-marathi-films-curves|title=Why should women look like men: Vidya Balan|work=The Times of India|accessdate=17 October 2012|date=31 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/movie_story.aspx?Section=Movies&ID=227385&subcatg=&keyword=Bollywood&nid=227385|title=Fat, so? Vidya is living large & loving it|publisher=NDTV|accessdate=18 October 2012|date=5 June 2012}}</ref>    

The mass media has often speculated about a romantic relationship between Balan and her co-actors, but she has strongly denied these reports.<ref>{{cite news|work=India Today|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/Poor+Vidya+pays+price+of+link-ups+with+stars/1/98590.html|date=24 May 2010|accessdate=7 October 2012|title=Poor Vidya pays price of link-ups with stars|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6CJF7T13e|archivedate=20 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Tabloid/Vidya-happy-she-s-not-linked-to-Arshad/Article1-350110.aspx|title=Vidya happy she is not linked to Arshad|work=Hindustan Times|accessdate=11 October 2012|date=8 November 2008}}</ref> In 2009, Balan was involved in a controversy when she mentioned a previous relationship in which "caustic remarks" were made at her due to her weight. She said, "If someone who matters to you takes you down, it can break you. That someone whose approval mattered to me started to constantly find faults with me. At that point of time, it was important to walk away from that relationship."<ref>{{cite news|last=Lalwani|first=Vickey|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-11-14/news-interviews/28068480_1_weight-loss-paa-and-ishqiya-vidya-balan |title=Vidya opens up on Shahid |work=The Times of India|accessdate=11 May 2012|date=14 November 2009}}</ref> Though she refused to name the person, [[tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] reports suggested that she was referring to Shahid Kapoor (her co-star in ''Kismat Konnection'').<ref>{{cite web|last=Mahadevan|first=Sneha|title=W(eig)ht so funny?!|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2467778891.html|work=Daily News and Analysis {{Subscription required|via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}|accessdate=17 October 2012|date=25 September 2011}}</ref> Kapoor, however, denied the allegations.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.hindustantimes.com/Brunch/Brunch-Stories/Shahid-Kapoor-uncut/Article1-877077.aspx|title=Shahid Kapoor, uncut |work=Hindustan Times|accessdate=11 May 2012|date=22 June 2012}}</ref> During an interview in May 2012, Balan announced that she was dating [[Siddharth Roy Kapur]], the CEO of [[UTV Motion Pictures]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/i-am-dating-siddharth-roy-kapoor-vidya-balan/256908-8-66.html|title=I am dating Siddharth Roy Kapoor: Vidya Balan |publisher=IBNLive|accessdate=11 May 2012|date=11 May 2012}}</ref> Balan and Kapur are going to get married on 14 December 2012.

Besides acting in film, Balan is a social activist. In March 2011, Balan endorsed [[World Wildlife Fund]]'s [[Earth Hour]] campaign in India.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wadhwa|first=Akash|url= http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-03-17/news-interviews/28699077_1_earth-hour-vidya-balan-wwf |title=Vidya Balan to promote Earth Hour|work=The Times of India|accessdate=24 September 2012|date=17 March 2011}}</ref>
She campaigned for the cause of nutrition in India for CINI (Child in Need Institute), a non-profit organisation based in Kolkata.<ref>{{cite news|last=Chatterjee|first=Chandreyee|url= http://www.telegraphindia.com/1120529/jsp/calcutta/story_15541666.jsp#.UF_9r40gejs |title=Canvas to canvass for nutrition cause|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=24 September 2012|date=29 May 2012}}</ref> In September 2012, Balan visited a village in [[Mirzapur]], Uttar Pradesh, where she participated in a campaign to promote the cause of women empowerment and children's education.<ref>{{cite news|last=Udasi|first=Harshikaa|url= http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article3877583.ece |title=Doing her bit for society|work=The Hindu|accessdate=24 September 2012|date=9 September 2012}}</ref> For her contribution in the field of women empowerment, Balan was awarded with The Prabha Khaitan Puraskar 2012 by the Calcutta Chamber of Commerce, and emerged as the youngest recipient of the award.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vidya Balan bags another award, but not for a film!|url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2675120141.html |work=Daily News and Analysis {{Subscription required|via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}|accessdate=24 September 2012|date=1 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-05-31/news-interviews/31919963_1_women-centric-films-bengali-films-satyajit-ray |title=Women-centric films reflect changing society: Vidya Balan|work=The Times of India|accessdate=24 September 2012|date=31 May 2012}}</ref> Balan has also been appointed by the [[Government of India]] as their brand ambassador in the drive to improve the country's sanitary condition.<ref>{{cite news|last=Chakravorty|first=Vinayak|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/indiahome/indianews/article-2140168/Celebs-cause-Vidya-Balan-latest-long-line-Bollywood-stars-getting-involved-philanthropy.html |title=Celebs with a cause: Vidya Balan is only the latest in a long line of Bollywood stars getting involved in philanthropy|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=24 September 2012|date=6 May 2012}}</ref>

==Media image and artistry==
[[File:Vidya Balan at Melbourne Cricket Ground (3).jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=A black-haired woman holds a soccer ball with both her hands. She is wearing a bright red sari with her hair falling on her shoulders.|Balan at the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]], 2012]]
Following the success of ''Parineeta'' and ''Lage Raho Munnabhai'', Balan's film roles were subject to wide critical analysis.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2011/20110410/spectrum/main9.htm|title=The uniqueness of being Vidya|work=The Tribune|accessdate=17 October 2012|date=10 April 2011}}</ref> [[Vir Sanghvi]] noted that the films ''Heyy Babyy'' and ''Kismet Konnection'' were "strange films [...] in which she tried to pretend to be what she is not&nbsp;<U+2014> a Bollywood bimbette."<ref name="rules"/> Balan described that particular phase in her career as a "struggle to be someone else".<ref>{{cite news|last=Bhupta|first=Malini|url= http://indiatoday.in/womansummit/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&issueid=34&id=2677&Itemid=1&sectionid=1 |title=It's a constant struggle to be someone else: Vidya|work=India Today|accessdate=23 September 2012}}</ref> Due to the criticism that her film choices evoked, Balan decided to choose roles that she "believed in" rather than choose by convention.<ref name="men">{{cite news|title=Why men love Vidya Balan|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-246310012.html |work=Hindustan Times {{Subscription required|via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}|accessdate=23 September 2012|date=12 January 2011}}</ref> Members of the media have subsequently labelled her as "bold" and "daring" in her choices.<ref name="list">{{cite web|last=Sen|first=Raja|title=Bollywood's best actresses of 2011|url= http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-bollywoods-best-actresses-of-the-year-yearend-2011/20111230.htm |publisher=Rediff.com|accessdate=23 September 2012|date=30 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Vidya Balan: Hindi cinema's new bold|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/vidya-balan-hindi-cinemas-new-bold/890115/0 |work=The Indian Express|accessdate=23 September 2012|date=21 December 2011}}</ref>

Her starring roles in ''Heyy Babyy'' and ''Kismet Konnection'' also led to considerable attention in the media for her "questionable wardrobe". Several publications listed her as the "worst dressed actress" and her costume designers attributed her failure to carry off western clothes due to her weight and body structure.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wadhwa|first=Akash|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2008-09-14/news-interviews/27891870_1_vidya-balan-parineeta-kismat-konnection|title=Look, it does matter!|work=The Times of India|accessdate=17 October 2012|date=14 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=Rediff.com|title=The worst dressed actresses of 2007|date=4 December 2007|url=http://specials.rediff.com/yearend/2007/dec/04yractress1.htm|accessdate=23 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=What was she thinking?|url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1495143311.html|work=Hindustan Times {{Subscription required|via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}|accessdate=23 September 2012|date=15 June 2008}}</ref> She was later praised in the media for wearing [[sari]]s at public events; designer Niharika Khan explained, "Vidya's beauty lies in her curves. She's comfortable in her voluptuousness, and therefore in a sari."<ref>{{cite news|last=Walia|first=Nona|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-26/designers/31144727_1_vidya-balan-sari-heyy-babyy |title=Is Vidya Balan trapped in a sari? |work=The Times of India|accessdate=23 September 2012|date=26 April 2012}}</ref> Balan has since been identified to defy "an anglicised idea of sexuality" and embody the idea of "raw Indian sexuality".<ref name="men"/>

After portraying headstrong, independent women in ''Paa'', ''Ishqiya'', ''No One Killed Jessica'', ''The Dirty Picture'' and ''Kahaani'', Balan was credited in the media for breaking stereotypes of a Hindi film heroine.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bhirani|first=Radhika|title=Vidya Balan oozes oomph in The Dirty Picture|url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-266836719.html|work=Qatar Tribune {{Subscription required|via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}|accessdate=13 October 2012|date=13 September 2011}}</ref> The major commercial success of the latter two also contributed to her being labelled as a "female hero".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/tabloid/bengaluru/vidya-hero-ine-making-033 |title=Is Vidya the hero-ine in the making?|work=Deccan Chronicle|accessdate=23 September 2012|date=11 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Naval-Shetye|first=Aakanksha|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report_im-happy-being-called-a-heroine-vidya-balan_1623410|title=I'm happy being called a heroine: Vidya Balan|work=Daily News and Analysis|accessdate=17 October 2012|date=9 December 2011}}</ref> Film critic [[Mayank Shekhar]] predicted, "Just a few smart male actors can completely change the face of a commercial, star-driven film industry. Looking at [...] Vidya Balan [...] it appears, that change could well originate from the leading lady instead."<ref>{{cite news|last=Shekar|first=Mayank|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Reviews/Mayank-Shekhar-s-review-The-Dirty-Picture/Article1-777101.aspx|title=Mayank Shekhar's review: The Dirty Picture|work=Hindustan Times|accessdate=23 September 2012|date=2 December 2011}}</ref> ''[[India Today]]'' featured her in their listing of the "25 Power Women" and noted that "she has toppled the all dominating hero, reducing him to a supporting role in a male dominated film industry".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/25-most-influential-women-vidya-balan-kareena-kapoor/1/177016.html|title=25 power women and their inspiring stories|work=India Today|accessdate=23 September 2012|date=9 March 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6CJF91OtB|archivedate=20 November 2012}}</ref>

Balan occupied the top slot in Rediff.com's annual listing of "Bollywood's Best Actress" for two consecutive years (2010<U+2013>11).<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Rediff.com|title=Bollywood's best actresses, 2010|date=31 December 2010|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-bollywoods-best-ctresses-2010/20101231.htm|accessdate=23 September 2012}}</ref><ref name="list"/> She also featured in the list for the years 2005, 2006 and 2009.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Rediff.com|title=Bollywood's best actresses, 2005|date=23 December 2005|url=http://specials.rediff.com/yearend/2005/dec/23yend9.htm|accessdate=23 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=Rediff.com|title=Bollywood's top actresses, 2006|date=25 August 2006|url=http://specials.rediff.com/movies/2006/aug/25sd4.htm|accessdate=23 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=Rediff.com|title=Bollywood's best actresses, 2009|date=31 December 2009|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-best-actresses-of-2009/20091231.htm|accessdate=23 September 2012}}</ref>
In 2010, she featured in ''[[Filmfare]]'''s listing of the "Women we love".<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.filmfare.com/articles/women-we-love-story-part-47-703.html|title=Women we love story Part 1/7|accessdate=11 July 2012|date=12 April 2012|journal=Filmfare|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20100417204252/http://www.filmfare.com/articles/women-we-love-part-47-703.html|archivedate=16 April 2012}}</ref> In 2012, the magazine ''Verve'' listed her as one of India's "Young Power Women" and wrote, "In a reel world peopled by [[size zero]]-toned bodies and pretty-as-a-picture heroines, Balan comes across as completely real and natural&nbsp;<U+2013> a woman who has followed her own instincts and dared to live her destiny by being her own person and not morphing herself to fit into any conventional slot."<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.verveonline.com/109/people/power-women.shtml|title=Young power women|author=Mehta, S., Jahagirdar-Saxena, S., Modak, N. & Sah, M.|journal=Verve|volume=20|issue=6|accessdate=23 September 2012|year=2012|month=June}}</ref>

